TPS Central: AI Agent Strategy
Case Study | Adobe Technical Pre-Sales
Beckie Cole — Director, Strategy & Business Operations, Technical Pre-Sales
---
The Shift
TPS Ops was the intermediary between data and decisions — assembling reports, answering platform questions, responding to support requests, and facilitating leadership cadences. This proposal eliminates that intermediary role entirely.
GTM leaders self-serve intelligence. Tech Drivers get real-time deal guidance. Platform questions get instant answers. The team shifts from producing intelligence to designing the systems that produce it.
Capacity recovered: 25-40 hours/week redeployed from reporting and help-desk work to signal design and strategic analysis.
---
Three Agents, One Platform
All four deliverables run on a single stack: Copilot Studio for AI reasoning and conversational interfaces, Power Automate for data connectivity and system writes, SharePoint for durable artifact storage. No new platforms, no new auth, no new maintenance burden.
Deliverable	What It Does	Who It Serves
TPS Central Agent	Keeps TPS Central current; surfaces real-time deal guidance	Tech Drivers / ICs
Janet — Ask Janet	Answers GTM leaders' operational questions grounded in live data	FLMs, Directors, SLMs
TPS Central Support Agent	Answers "how do I" questions instantly across 93 documented intents	Everyone
Friday GTM Briefing Package	Automated weekly briefing deck + Excel workbooks per vertical	GTM Leadership
Three agents, not four. Early thinking explored a separate "TPS Action Agent" for next best actions. That capability already lives across two agents: the TPS Central Agent surfaces deal-level actions to Tech Drivers, Janet surfaces portfolio-level actions to leadership. A fourth agent creates confusion, not capability.
Three agents, not two. Collapsing Janet and the Support Agent would conflate two distinct jobs: "what's happening with my business" vs. "how do I use this system." Different knowledge bases, different audiences, different answer patterns.
---
TPS Central Agent
The Tech Driver's AI-powered interface for keeping TPS Central current and getting real-time deal guidance. Design principle: input + feedback agent. Makes it easy to put data in and immediately returns value. Every update improves the data powering Janet, the Support Agent, and the Friday Package — a flywheel where all agents make each other more valuable.
Evolution Path
Layer	Capability	Timeline
Layer 1: Touchpoint Logging	Reads TD calendar, classifies against 22 touchpoint types, resolves to correct opp, writes to Workfront	Weeks 1-4
Layer 2: TD Field Updates	Interprets natural language to update 9 TD validation fields	Weeks 5-8
Layer 3: NBA Read-Back	After updates, checks for open NBA actions and surfaces top recommendation	Weeks 9-12
Layer 4: Full Agent	Request queries, document context, deal prep. Primary operating interface.	Q2+
Example Interaction (Layer 3)
> **Tech Driver:** Just finished the architecture review with Globex. Tech fit is confirmed — aligned on AEP + GenStudio. Seeing risk around their legacy integration layer though.
>
> **Agent:** Got it. Logged: Architecture Review touchpoint on DR-4521 (Globex Corp, $2.1M), Opp Tech Fit Confirmed, Opp Architecture Design Complete, Opp Tech Risk High. Since Tech Risk is now High with no mitigation plan, your next best action is to document the risk mitigation path. This deal closes in 6 weeks — time-sensitive. Want me to help draft the summary?
One conversation. Four system writes. One forward-looking recommendation. Zero time in the Workfront UI.
